/F1 10.20 Tf
1 0 0 1 64.00 777.89 Tm (The implemented collection stage performs only lightweight cleaning: empty records are removed, identifiers) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 766.09 Tm (are normalized, and all examples are rewritten into a common tabular structure. This restraint is) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 754.29 Tm (methodologically deliberate. Over-aggressive text normalization can destroy exactly those surface) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 742.49 Tm (irregularities that are relevant for humor, including orthographic play, punchline timing, and deliberately) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 730.69 Tm (awkward formulations. The current code therefore prefers a permissive collection strategy in which noise is) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 718.89 Tm (preserved unless it directly prevents downstream processing.) Tj
/F2 10.50 Tf
1 0 0 1 64.00 703.09 Tm (A staged view of semantic structure.) Tj
/F1 10.20 Tf
1 0 0 1 64.00 690.09 Tm (The codebase does not jump directly from raw jokes to prompts or references. Instead, it inserts) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 678.29 Tm (intermediate representational layers. This is motivated by the fact that humor is semantically dense but) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 666.49 Tm (lexically unstable: two jokes may be close in premise or mechanism even if they share little surface) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 654.69 Tm (vocabulary. A staged pipeline therefore offers a more reliable route from text to weak supervision than) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 642.89 Tm (exact matching would.) Tj
/F2 10.50 Tf
1 0 0 1 64.00 627.09 Tm (Expected distributional properties.) Tj
/F1 10.20 Tf
1 0 0 1 64.00 614.09 Tm (From a methodological point of view, the collected corpus should be expected to be uneven. Certain topics,) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 602.29 Tm (lexical triggers, and joke forms occur frequently, while others are rare. This is not merely an) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 590.49 Tm (inconvenience; it is part of the object of study. A prompt-oriented humor dataset naturally has a) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 578.69 Tm (heavy-tailed structure in which some weak constraints map to many jokes and others map to very few. The) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 566.89 Tm (current implementation preserves this structure rather than artificially smoothing it out, because later) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 555.09 Tm (stages such as retrieval and reference construction depend precisely on such non-uniform semantic) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 543.29 Tm (neighborhoods.) Tj
/F2 13.00 Tf
1 0 0 1 64.00 523.49 Tm (Semantic Enrichment and Reference Construction) Tj
/F2 10.50 Tf
1 0 0 1 64.00 506.49 Tm (Dense embeddings as a continuous semantic layer.) Tj
/F1 10.20 Tf
1 0 0 1 64.00 493.49 Tm (The first enrichment stage maps each joke to an embedding vector. Embeddings provide a continuous semantic) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 481.69 Tm (space in which related jokes can become neighbors even when their wording differs. This is especially useful) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 469.89 Tm (for humor, where paraphrase, indirection, and lexical novelty are common. By materializing embeddings as a) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 458.09 Tm (standalone dataset, the pipeline creates the geometric backbone for later retrieval operations.) Tj
/F2 10.50 Tf
1 0 0 1 64.00 442.29 Tm (Why embeddings come before prompt construction.) Tj
/F1 10.20 Tf
1 0 0 1 64.00 429.29 Tm (In principle, one could attempt to derive prompts directly from raw jokes with a language model. The current) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 417.49 Tm (implementation does not begin there. Instead, it first constructs a geometric semantic layer.) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 405.69 Tm (Methodologically, this provides a more stable substrate on which later approximations can operate. A dense) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 393.89 Tm (representation makes it possible to compare jokes, keywords, and weak prompts within a common space, which) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 382.09 Tm (is valuable when exact symbolic mappings are not yet available.) Tj
/F2 10.50 Tf
1 0 0 1 64.00 366.29 Tm (Keywords as an interpretable bottleneck.) Tj
/F1 10.20 Tf
1 0 0 1 64.00 353.29 Tm (The next stage extracts a small set of keywords for each joke. This step should be understood not as naive) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 341.49 Tm (keyword mining, but as semantic compression. The aim is to produce a sparse and interpretable representation) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 329.69 Tm (that captures salient constraints without preserving the whole text. In the implemented system, lexical) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 317.89 Tm (candidates are generated from the joke itself, embedded, and ranked against the embedding of the full joke.) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 306.09 Tm (Maximal marginal relevance balances relevance and diversity, so the final keywords function as compact) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 294.29 Tm (semantic handles that remain human-readable while still being grounded in the embedding space.) Tj
/F2 10.50 Tf
1 0 0 1 64.00 278.49 Tm (The role of diversity in keyword selection.) Tj
/F1 10.20 Tf
1 0 0 1 64.00 265.49 Tm (Diversity is an important methodological consideration here. If keyword extraction simply returned the most) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 253.69 Tm (frequent or most semantically similar terms, the output would often collapse into near-duplicates and fail) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 241.89 Tm (to express the constraint set of the joke. The use of diversity-aware selection acknowledges that a useful) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 230.09 Tm (weak prompt should ideally reflect several facets of a joke at once, for example topic, object, setting, or) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 218.29 Tm (mechanism. Even though the current implementation is lightweight, it already treats keyword extraction as a) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 206.49 Tm (constrained summarization problem rather than as a purely lexical one.) Tj
/F2 10.50 Tf
1 0 0 1 64.00 190.69 Tm (Retrieval as practical prompt inversion.) Tj
/F1 10.20 Tf
1 0 0 1 64.00 177.69 Tm (The broader thesis proposes converting jokes into prompts so that many jokes can be grouped under shared) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 165.89 Tm (weak constraints. The current implementation realizes a practical approximation of this idea. Instead of) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 154.09 Tm (asking a language model to infer prompts for every joke, it forms weak prompt-like queries from keyword) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 142.29 Tm (combinations and retrieves semantically similar jokes in embedding space. Conceptually, this is an) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 130.49 Tm (inversion-by-retrieval strategy: a joke is compressed into salient cues, these cues are expanded into weak) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 118.69 Tm (prompts, and those prompts are used to recover a neighborhood of plausible references.) Tj
/F1 9.00 Tf
