/F1 10.20 Tf
1 0 0 1 64.00 777.89 Tm (This approximation is methodologically defensible. Direct prompt extraction is flexible, but it is also) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 766.09 Tm (expensive and may introduce instability or hallucinated constraints. The implemented retrieval-based route) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 754.29 Tm (sacrifices some expressivity in exchange for reproducibility and control. It still preserves the key) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 742.49 Tm (structural idea needed for later training: the same weak semantic seed can point to multiple acceptable) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 730.69 Tm (jokes. Thus, the current code already instantiates a multi-reference view of humor, even if it does so) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 718.89 Tm (through keyword-guided retrieval rather than full prompt induction.) Tj
/F2 10.50 Tf
1 0 0 1 64.00 703.09 Tm (From keyword groups to weak constraints.) Tj
/F1 10.20 Tf
1 0 0 1 64.00 690.09 Tm (A particularly important feature of the implementation is that it does not restrict itself to a single) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 678.29 Tm (keyword view of each joke. Instead, it forms several keyword groups and turns them into prompt-like queries.) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 666.49 Tm (Methodologically, this matters because humorous texts are often multiply interpretable. One joke can be) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 654.69 Tm (indexed through a topical cue, a relation between concepts, or a more specific object or phrase. Generating) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 642.89 Tm (several weak constraints from the same joke is therefore a way of approximating the fact that a single) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 631.09 Tm (humorous text may belong to several semantic families at once.) Tj
/F2 10.50 Tf
1 0 0 1 64.00 615.29 Tm (Multi-reference structure as the central target.) Tj
/F1 10.20 Tf
1 0 0 1 64.00 602.29 Tm (The ultimate goal of these transformations is not retrieval for its own sake. It is the construction of a) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 590.49 Tm (dataset in which one weak semantic seed is linked to multiple plausible joke references. This is the key) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 578.69 Tm (property needed for the broader thesis, because it shifts the supervision problem away from a single correct) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 566.89 Tm (answer and toward a partially observed set of good answers. The current code reaches this structure) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 555.09 Tm (operationally by storing, for each identifier and keyword group, a list of retrieved references with) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 543.29 Tm (associated similarity scores.) Tj
/F2 10.50 Tf
1 0 0 1 64.00 527.49 Tm (Indexing and scalability.) Tj
/F1 10.20 Tf
1 0 0 1 64.00 514.49 Tm (The use of FAISS for reference retrieval is also part of the methodological design rather than a purely) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 502.69 Tm (technical convenience. A multi-reference dataset is only useful if it can be constructed over hundreds of) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 490.89 Tm (thousands of examples, which makes naive all-pairs comparison impractical. Approximate nearest-neighbor) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 479.09 Tm (search therefore provides a scalable approximation to semantic grouping.) Tj
/F2 10.50 Tf
1 0 0 1 64.00 463.29 Tm (Methodological limitations of retrieval-based inversion.) Tj
/F1 10.20 Tf
1 0 0 1 64.00 450.29 Tm (At the same time, the current implementation should not be mistaken for a perfect realization of prompt) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 438.49 Tm (induction. Retrieval neighborhoods can reflect superficial topical similarity without fully preserving the) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 426.69 Tm (underlying comedic mechanism. Keyword-based weak constraints may underspecify the joke, overspecify it, or) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 414.89 Tm (privilege objects over relations. In addition, nearest-neighbor retrieval can return the original joke or) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 403.09 Tm (jokes that are semantically adjacent but not truly interchangeable as references. These limitations do not) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 391.29 Tm (invalidate the approach, but they clarify what kind of supervision the present pipeline actually constructs:) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 379.49 Tm (a pragmatic approximation to a multi-reference prompt dataset, not a final canonical form of it.) Tj
/F2 10.50 Tf
1 0 0 1 64.00 363.69 Tm (Why the approximation is still useful.) Tj
/F1 10.20 Tf
1 0 0 1 64.00 350.69 Tm (Despite these limitations, the current design remains valuable for research. It already enforces the shift) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 338.89 Tm (from isolated examples to structured neighborhoods; it already separates dense and sparse representations;) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 327.09 Tm (and it already exposes candidate reference sets that can be inspected, filtered, or rescored later. In other) Tj
1 0 0 1 64.00 315.29 Tm (words, the implemented pipeline does not solve the full prompt construction problem, but it creates the data) Tj
